{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14089"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14089"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.55,0.1,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92945"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6757"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2980"},{"type":"tags","id":"3640"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5495"},{"type":"tags","id":"11618"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12918"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44987"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92945"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of high fever, dry cough, and progressive shortness of breath. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. His regular medications include metformin and ramipril. He works as a hotel manager.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals crackles in the right lower zone. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation. Urinary antigen test is positive for Legionella pneumophila serogroup 1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is commenced on antibiotic therapy and supplemental oxygen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional management steps is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Implement droplet precautions","Notify public health authorities","Isolate in negative pressure room","Initiate contact tracing","Recommend prophylaxis for family members"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case of confirmed Legionella pneumonia, the most appropriate management option is to \u003Cstrong\u003Enotify public health authorities\u003C/strong\u003E. Legionellosis is a notifiable disease in many countries, including Australia. Prompt notification is crucial for public health surveillance, outbreak detection, and implementation of control measures to prevent further cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELegionella pneumophila\u003C/em\u003E is transmitted through the inhalation of aerosols containing the bacteria, typically from contaminated water sources. The bacteria thrive in warm, stagnant water and can colonise various man-made water systems such as air conditioning cooling towers, hot water tanks and large plumbing systems. Public health authorities will likely initiate an investigation to identify the source of the infection, including an environmental exposure assessment and sampling of potential sources. If a source is identified, appropriate decontamination measures can then be implemented to prevent further cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImplementing droplet precautions\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for Legionella pneumonia. The bacteria cannot survive for long outside of water or a host, and they do not spread through respiratory droplets or aerosols produced by infected individuals. Standard precautions are sufficient for patient care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending prophylaxis for family members\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated. Since Legionella is not transmitted from person to person, family members are not at increased risk unless they were exposed to the same environmental source.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsolating in negative pressure room\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for Legionella pneumonia. This level of isolation is typically reserved for airborne infections such as tuberculosis or measles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating contact tracing \u003C/strong\u003Eis not necessary for Legionella pneumonia. Unlike diseases spread through person-to-person transmission, contact tracing is not useful in preventing the spread of Legionella. Identifying the source of infection is more important than tracing human contacts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Public health notification is mandatory for cases of Legionella pneumonia to facilitate outbreak investigation and prevention.","Environmental assessment of potential sources, such as cooling towers and water systems, is crucial in controlling Legionella outbreaks.","Isolation precautions are not necessary for patients with Legionella pneumonia as person-to-person transmission is extremely rare."],"references":["Communicable Diseases Network Australia. Legionellosis \u2013 CDNA National Guidelines for Public Health Units. In: Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care [online]; 2017. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/legionellosis-cdna-national-guidelines-for-public-health-units?language=en"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76298"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14089"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76298"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T10:28:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-31T03:03:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6757"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92945"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships